===Etymology 1===
[[Image:Biber-drawing.jpg|thumb|Beavers]]
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|bever|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|beofor||beaver|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|bebruz||beaver|lang=gem-pro}} (compare Dutch {{term|bever|lang=nl}}, French {{term|bièvre|lang=fr}}, German {{term|Biber|lang=de}}, Swedish dialect {{term|bjur|lang=sv}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|bʰébʰrus||beaver|lang=ine-pro}} (compare {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|befer|lang=cy}}, {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|fiber|lang=la}}, {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|bebras|bẽbras|lang=lt}}, {{etyl|ru|-}} {{term|бобр||tr=bobr|lang=ru}}, {{etyl|ae|-}} {{term|||tr=bawra|lang=ae}}, {{term|||tr=bawri|lang=ae}} {{rfscript|Avestan}}, {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term|बभ्रु||tr=bábru|mongoose; ichneumon|lang=sa}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|bʰreu-||shining, brown|lang=ine-pro}}. Related to [[brown]] and [[bear]].

====Noun====
{{en-noun|pl2=beaver}}

# An [[aquatic]] [[rodent]] of the genus ''[[Castor]]'', having a wide, flat tail and webbed feet.
# A hat, of various shape, made from a felted beaver fur, fashionable in Europe between 1550 and 1850
# {{non-gloss definition|A possibly different "beaver hat" is mentioned by Chaucer in both ''Canterbury Tales'' and ''Testament of Creeside'', and indeed much earlier in Normandy ''Chronicle of the Abbey of St Wandrille'' refers to a hat given before 833 as "quem vulgaris Bevurum".}}<ref>Notes and Queries Vol. 1 (21) 23  March 1850 Page 338</ref>
# {{context|coarse|slang}} The [[pubic hair]] and/or [[vulva]] of a woman.

